{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17513699","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17513699"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:12:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:12:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12191"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12191","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12191"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.36,0.54,0.03,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4719"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56950"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4719","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4719"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12191"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42404"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"1106"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7412"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7631"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17339"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56950","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/56950"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn otherwise healthy 20-year-old man was sitting, having a conversation with his mother when all of a sudden, he began smacking his lips, starring into space, appeared confused, and kept mumbling the same word repeatedly. This episode lasted approximately 15-20 seconds after which he suddenly became asymptomatic although he seemed slightly confused for a few minutes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis ?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Generalized tonic clonic seizures","Absence seizures","Focal motor with impaired awareness seizures","Myoclonic seizures","Psychogenic non-epileptiform seizures"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn this case of a 20-year-old man, \u003Cstrong\u003EFocal motor with impaired awareness seizure\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely diagnosis given his age and presentation, although absence seizures are also a possibility. A focal motor with impaired awareness seizure presents as impaired consciousness, these patients may also exhibit automatisms, such as lip smacking, chewing, gesturing, repeated swallowing, repeating words or phrases, walking, running, undressing, snapping fingers, or some other type of complex motor activity that is not specifically directed and is not appropriate. Following the seizure, these patients appear confused and disoriented for a few minutes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn contrast, \u003Cstrong\u003Eabsence seizures\u003C/strong\u003E present with a lapse in attention. Although automatisms can occur in absence seizure, absence spells occur without aura and are not associated with postictal confusion. Therefore, as the patient has post-ictal confusion, absence seizures are less likely. Note that absence seizures can occur at any age but more common in children.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGeneralized tonic-clonic seizures\u003C/strong\u003E are preceded by a prodrome occurring hours or days before a seizure. Common prodromes include mood changes, sleep disturbances, lightheadedness, anxiety, irritability, and difficulty concentrating. These are typically divided into tonic (stiffening) and clonic (twitching or jerking) phases of muscle activity followed by a postictal phase of confusion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPsychogenic non-epileptiform seizures \u003C/strong\u003Eare behavioral paroxysms that mimic epileptic seizures. Although its clinical picture resembles that of epileptic seizure including attention loss, loss of consciousness, lack of awareness, confusion or a blank prolonged stare but they are a manifestation of psychological distress. Both epileptic seizures and psychogenic non-epileptiform seizures can exist in the one patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Emyoclonic\u003C/strong\u003E seizure happens when muscles suddenly contract, causing quick twitching movements usually in the morning. It usually affects one side of the body and involves the neck, shoulders, and upper arms. It can also affect the whole body and the patient usually remains conscious.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A focal motor with impaired awareness seizure presents with motor activity and impaired awareness"],"references":["Muro VM, Connolly MB. 2014. Classifying epileptic seizures and the epilepsies. In Epilepsy (ed. Miller JW, Goodkin HP), pp. 10\u201314. Wiley, Chichester.","uff JS, Fountain NB. Pathophysiology and definitions of seizures and status epilepticus. Emerg Med Clin North Am. 2011 Feb;29(1):1-13.","Weisenberg, JLZ. Absence seizures. BMJ Best Practice. 2024. Available from: https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/115"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42404"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12191"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42404","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/42404"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-22T20:55:58+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-22T20:56:26+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4719"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56950"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"u